C:\Users\georg\.claude\projects\D--Tresorit-z-Keepass-GSP-AI-Claude-ws02-Claudes-Daily-Diary

● Not a persnicky question at all — it's a fair one. The honest answer is: no, they can't be moved there, and it's
  not really possible to change this.

  Those .jsonl files are Claude Code's conversation logs — the CLI writes them automatically to
  C:\Users\georg\.claude\projects\{project-path}\ based on a hash of your working directory. It's hardcoded
  behaviour; there's no setting to redirect them into the project folder itself.

  There's also a good reason they live outside the project: they contain the full raw transcript of every session
  (including any sensitive info you might have typed), so you wouldn't want them accidentally committed to git or
  synced to the VM via Tresorit.

  The practical approach is just to periodically delete old .jsonl files you no longer need — they're only useful
  if you want to resume a specific past session, which is rare. Other than that, they're Claude Code's housekeeping
   files and that location is where they'll always end up.



❯ But what about these fils on the other machines - doesn't this become a little disjointed?

● Yes, exactly — that's the inherent tension here:

  - .jsonl session logs are machine-local by design (and should stay that way — they're large, potentially
  sensitive, and not useful cross-machine)
  - Memories are the thing that should travel, which is why we moved them into the Tresorit-synced project folder

  So the setup is actually working as intended now:

  ┌──────────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────┐
  │         What         │                Where                │             Syncs?              │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Conversation history │ C:\Users\georg\.claude\projects\... │ No — machine-local, that's fine │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Memories             │ .claude/memory/ in project          │ Yes — via Tresorit              │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Skills, settings     │ .claude/ in project                 │ Yes — via Tresorit              │
  ├──────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Code, diary entries  │ project root                        │ Yes — via Tresorit + GitHub     │
  └──────────────────────┴─────────────────────────────────────┴─────────────────────────────────┘

  On another machine, Claude won't have the session history — but it will have the memories, skills, and CLAUDE.md,
   which is everything needed to pick up where you left off. The session logs are just raw transcripts; the
  distilled knowledge is in the memory files.

  The slight awkwardness is that on a new machine, Claude Code will start fresh .jsonl logs there. That's expected
  and fine — it's not information loss that matters.



